	  <title>Self Test: Types of Linear Transformations</title>
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>For each of the statements below indicate if it is true or false.</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>The matrix</para.body>
               </para>
				           <math.display>
					             <latex>
						
T =
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
3 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 3
\end{array}
\right]

					</latex>
				           </math.display>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>represents the dilation of <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                     </math> by a factor of <math>
                        <latex>3</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>True</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Recall the transformation effect of a matrix of the form <math>
                        <latex>c\cdot \IdMtrx[2]</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>One way to solve this problem is by remembering that a matrix of the form <math>
                           <latex>c\cdot \IdMtrx[2]</latex>
                        </math> rescales <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                        </math> by a factor of <math>
                           <latex>c</latex>
                        </math>. – This means that the statement in question is true.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>True</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Compute the transformation effect of <math>
                        <latex>T</latex>
                     </math> on an arbitrary vector <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x} = (x,y)</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>The matrix <math>
                           <latex>T</latex>
                        </math> represents the linear map <math>
                           <latex>L</latex>
                        </math> which transforms a vector <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x} = (x,y)</latex>
                        </math> into</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
L(\Vect{x}) =
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
3 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 3
\end{array}
\right]
\left[
\begin{array}{c} x \\ y \end{array}
\right] =
\left[
\begin{array}{c} 3x \\ 3y \end{array}
\right] = 3\Vect{x}

						</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>This means that <math>
                           <latex>L</latex>
                        </math> rescales <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                        </math> by a factor of <math>
                           <latex>3</latex>
                        </math> or, in other words, <math>
                           <latex>L</latex>
                        </math> is the dilation of <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                        </math> by the factor of <math>
                           <latex>3</latex>
                        </math>. – This means that the statement in question is true.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>The matrix</para.body>
               </para>
				           <math.display>
					             <latex>
						
T =
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
3 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 3
\end{array}
\right]

					</latex>
				           </math.display>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>represents the dilation of <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[4]</latex>
                     </math> by a factor of <math>
                        <latex>3</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>False</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Check the domain and the target of this transformation</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>The matrix <math>
                           <latex>T</latex>
                        </math> describes a transformation of <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                        </math>, not of <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[4]</latex>
                        </math>. Therefore the statement in question is false.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>The matrix</para.body>
               </para>
				           <math.display>
					             <latex>
						
T =
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
3 &amp; 3 \\
3 &amp; 3
\end{array}
\right]

					</latex>
				           </math.display>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>represents the dilation of <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                     </math> by a factor of <math>
                        <latex>3</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>False</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Check if this transformation transforms an arbitrary vector <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math> into the vector <math>
                        <latex>3\cdot \Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>The matrix <math>
                           <latex>T</latex>
                        </math> transforms a vector <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x} = (x,y)</latex>
                        </math> into the vector <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{y} = (3x+3y,3x+3y)</latex>
                        </math>. Such a vector <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                        </math> can be distinct from <math>
                           <latex>3\cdot \Vect{x}</latex>
                        </math>. For example, <math>
                           <latex>T</latex>
                        </math> transforms <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x} = (1,-1)</latex>
                        </math> into <math>
                           <latex>(0,0)\neq 3\cdot (1,-1)</latex>
                        </math>. Therefore the statement in question is false.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>The matrix</para.body>
               </para>
				           <math.display>
					             <latex>
						
R =
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
1 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 0
\end{array}
\right]

					</latex>
				           </math.display>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>represents the projection of <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                     </math> onto the <math>
                        <latex>x</latex>
                     </math>-axis.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>True</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Recall: <math>
                        <latex>\Prjctn{1}\from \RNr[2] \to \RNr</latex>
                     </math> satisfies <math>
                        <latex>\Prjctn{1}(x,y)=x</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>We determine the transformation effect of <math>
                           <latex>R</latex>
                        </math>:</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>
							
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
1 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 0
\end{array}
\right] \left[ \begin{array}{c} x \\ y \end{array} \right] = 
\left[ \begin{array}{c} x \\ 0 \end{array} \right]

						</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>On the other hand, the projection of <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                        </math> onto the <math>
                           <latex>x</latex>
                        </math>-axis is given by</para.body>
                  </para>
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>\Prjctn{1}\from \RNr[2] \to \RNr,\qquad \Prjctn{1}(x,y)=x</latex>
					             </math.display>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>The two transformations have the same effect on each vector of <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                        </math>. So, they are equal. – Therefore the statement in question is true.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>The matrix</para.body>
               </para>
				           <math.display>
					             <latex>
						
R =
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
0 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 1
\end{array}
\right]

					</latex>
				           </math.display>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>represents the projection of <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                     </math> onto the <math>
                        <latex>y</latex>
                     </math>-axis.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>True</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
					          <para>
                  <para.body>Recall: <math>
                        <latex>\Prjctn{2}\from \RNr[2] \to \RNr</latex>
                     </math> satisfies <math>
                        <latex>\Prjctn{2}(x,y)=y</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
				        </solution.hint>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
	  </exercise>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>For which values of <math>
                     <latex>s</latex>
                  </math> is the scaling transformation of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math>,</para.body>
            </para>
			         <math.display>
				           <latex>L\from \RNr[2] \longrightarrow \RNr[2],\quad L(\Vect{x})=s\cdot \Vect{x}</latex>
			         </math.display>
			         <para>
               <para.body>also a rotation of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math> about the origin?</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <approach version="1">
			      <solution.hint>
				        <para>
               <para.body>A rotation leaves the size and shape of an object unchanged. For which values of <math>
                     <latex>s</latex>
                  </math> does <math>
                     <latex>L</latex>
                  </math> do this?</para.body>
            </para>
			      </solution.hint>
			      <solution>
            <solution.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>A rotation leaves the size and shape of an object unchanged. The only values of <math>
                        <latex>s</latex>
                     </math> for which <math>
                        <latex>L</latex>
                     </math> leaves sizes unchanged are</para.body>
               </para>
				           <ol>
					             <li>
						               <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>s=1</latex>
                           </math> which is the identity transformation. Indeed, this may also be viewed as the rotation about the origin of <math>
                              <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                           </math> through the angle <math>
                              <latex>0</latex>
                           </math>.</para.body>
                     </para>
					             </li>
					             <li>
						               <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>s=-1</latex>
                           </math> which is the reflection through the origin. Indeed, this may also be viewed as the rotation about the origin of <math>
                              <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                           </math> through the angle <math>
                              <latex>\pi</latex>
                           </math>.</para.body>
                     </para>
					             </li>
				           </ol>
			         </solution.body>
         </solution>
		    </approach>
	  </exercise>
